was compared with a public domain hard copy(165,9)of the text.





  ETYMOLOGY.


  (Supplied by a Late Consumptive Usher to a Grammar School.)

  The pale Usher—threadbare in coat, heart, body, and brain; I see him
  now. He was ever dusting his old lexicons and grammars,(264,8)queer
  handkerchief, mockingly embellish(315,9)ll the gay flags of(21,8)
  known nations(1244,8)world. He loved to dust(163,9)(150,8); it
  somehow mildly reminded him of his mortality.

  “While you take in hand to school others, and to teach them by what
  name a whale-fish is to be called in our tongue, leaving out, through
  ignorance, the letter H, which almost alone maketh up the
  signific(952,9)the word, you deliver that which is not true.”
  —_Hackluyt._

  “WHALE. * * * Sw. and Dan. _hval_. This animal is named from
  roundness or rolling; for in(70,11)t_ is arched or vaulted.”
  —_Webster’s Dictionary(158,20)It is more immediately(1200,10)Dut. and Ger. _Wallen_;
  A.S. _Walw-ian_, to roll, to wallow.” —_Richardson(141,17)
  חו,        (8,8) _Hebrew_.
  ϰητος(35,15)_Greek_.
  CETUS(31,16)Latin_.
  WHŒL(96,16)_Anglo-Saxon_.
  HVALT(99,16)Danish_.
  WA(68,17) _Dutch_.
  H(32,19)_Swed(64,9)HALE(195,16)Icelandic(35,26)Engl(132,8)BALLENA(300,13)_Sp(165,10)PEKEE-NUEE-NUEE,    _Fegee_.
