CHAPTER 1. Loomings.

Call me Ishmael. Some years ago—never mind how long precisely—having
little or no money in my purse, and nothing particular to interest me
on shore, I thought I would sail about a little and see(1377,10)y part
of the world. It is a way I have of driving off the spleen and
regulat(508,8)circulation. Whenever I find myself growing grim about
the mouth; w(53,8)it is a damp, drizzly November in my soul(52,10)
(105,14)involuntarily pausing before coffin warehouses, and
bringing up the rear of every funeral I meet; and especially(136,10)my hypos get such an upper hand of me, that it requires a strong moral
principle to prevent me from deliberately stepping(1815,10)street, and
methodically knocking people’s hats off—then, I account it high time to
get to sea as soon as I can. This is my substitute for pistol and ball.
With a philosophical flourish Cato throws himself upon his sword; I
quietly tak(1367,9)ship. There is(837,9)surprising in this. If they
but knew it, almost all men in their degree, some time or other,
cherish very nearly the same feelings towards the ocean with me.

There now is your insular city(1829,8)Manhattoes, belted round by
wharves as Indian isles by coral reefs—commerce surrounds(1641,9)her
surf. Right and left,(588,11)s take you waterward. Its extreme
downtown is the battery(1434,8)that noble mole is washed by wav(900,8)cooled by breezes, which a few hours previous were out of sight of
land. Look at the crowds of water-gazers there.

Circumambulate the(382,9)a dreamy Sabbath afternoon. Go from Corlears
Hook to Coenties Slip, and from thence, by Whitehall, northward. What
do you see?—Posted like silent sentinels all around the town, stand
thousands upon (15,10)of mortal men fixed in ocean reveries. Some
leaning against the spiles; some seated(99,8)e pier-heads; some
looking over the bulwarks of ships from China; some high aloft in the
rigging, as if striving to get a still better seaward peep. But these
are all landsmen; of week days pent up in lath and plaster—tied to
counters, nailed to benches, clinched to desks. How then is this? Are
the green fields gone? What do they here?

But look! here come mor(721,8), pacing straight for(2021,10), and
seemingly bound for a dive. Strange! Nothing will content them but the
extremest limit(1178,8)land; loitering under the shady lee of yonder
(1905,10) will not suffice. No. They must get just as nigh(215,10)
as they possibly can without falling in. And there they stand—miles of
them—leagues. Inlanders all, they co(1904,8)lanes and alleys,(1303,8)
and avenues—north, east, south, and west. Yet (141,10)all unite. Tell
me, does the magnetic virtue(1543,8)needles(1558,8)compasses of all
those ships attract them thither?

Once more. Say you are in the country; in(909,11)land of lakes. Take
(1838,8)ny path you please, and ten to one it carries you down in a
dale, and leaves you there by a pool(154,8)stream(2016,11)magic in
it. Let the most absent-minded of men be plunged in his deepest
(1269,8)—stand that man on his legs, set his feet a-going, and he will
infallibly lead you to(905,8)if water(223,8)e in all that region.
Should you ever be athirs(1291,8) great American desert, try this
experiment, if your caravan happen to be supplied with a metaphysical
professor. Yes, as every one knows, meditation and water are wedded for
ever.

But (439,8)an artist. He desires to paint(514,8) dreamiest, shadiest,
quietest, most enchanting bit of romantic landscap(359,11)e valley
of the Saco. What is the chief element he employs? There stand his
