Look now at the wondrous traditional story of how this island was
settled(269,8)red-men. Thus goes the legend. In olden times an eagle
swooped down upon the New England coast, and(771,9)off an infant
Indian in his talons. With loud lament the parents saw their child
borne out of sight over the wide waters. They resolved to follow in the
same direction. Setting out in(115,8)anoes(1625,9) perilous(1677,8)
they discovered the island, (1359,12)ey(569,8)n empty ivory
casket,—the poor little Indian’s skeleton.

What wonder, the(720,9)hese(1864,10)ers, born on a(1537,8)should
take(688,8)sea for a livelihood! They first caught crabs and quohogs
in the sand; grown bol(152,8)y waded out with nets for mackerel; more
experienced, they pushed off in boats and captured cod; and at last,
launching a navy of great ships on(237,8), explored this watery world;
put an incessant belt of circumnavigations round it; peeped in at
Behring’s Straits; and in all seasons and all oceans declared
everlasting war with the mightiest animated mass that has survived the
flood; most monstrous and(19,8)untainous! That Himmalehan, salt-sea
Mastodon, clothed with such portentousness of unconscious power, that
his very panics are more to be dreaded than his most fearless and
malicious assaults!

And thus have these naked(772,15)these sea hermits, issuing from
their ant-hill (725,8)ea, overrun and conqu(989,9)(565,12) like
so many Alexanders; parcell(1104,8)among them the Atlantic, Pacific,
and Indian oceans, as the three pirate powers did Poland. Let America
add Mexico to Texas, and pile Cuba upon Canada; let the English
overswarm all India, and hang out their blazing banner from the sun;
two thirds of this terraqueous globe are th(1206,13)’s. For(1179,8)
is his; he owns it, as Emperors own empires; other seamen having but a
right of way through it. Merchan(1064,8)are but extension bridges;
armed ones but floating forts; even pirates and privateers, though
following(1402,9)as highwaymen the roa(1288,8)but plunder(219,8)hips,
other fragments of the land like themselves, without seeking to draw
their liv(779,8) the bottomless deep itself. T(423,14), he alone
resides and riot(1389,12);(39,9), in Bible language, goes down to
it in ships; to and fro ploughing it as his own special plantation.
_There_ is his home; _there_ lies his business, which a Noah’s flood
would not interrupt(450,8) it overwhelmed all the millions in China.
He live(1659,14)as prairie cocks(1135,8)prairie; he hides among
the waves, he climbs them as chamois hunters climb the Alps. For years
he knows not(554,9); so that when he comes to it(1882,9) it smells
like another world, more strangely than the moon would to an Earthsman.
W(1748,8)landless gull, that at sunset folds her wings and is rocked to
sleep between billows; so at nightfall,(1122,16), out of sight
of land, furls his sails, and lays him to his rest, while under his
very pillow rush herds of walruses and whales.


