CHAPTER 27. Knights and Squires.

Stubb was the second mate. He was a native of Cape Cod; and hence,
according to local usage, was called a Cape-Cod-man. A happy-go-lucky;
neither craven nor valiant; taking perils as they came with an
indifferent air; and while engaged(1560,8)most imminent crisis of the
chase, toiling away, calm and collected as a journeyman joiner(106,8)
for the year. Good-humored, easy, and careless, he presided(1123,9)
whale-boat as if(1352,10)deadly encounter were but a dinner, and his
crew all invited guests(479,10)s particular about the comfortable
arrangement of his part of the boat, as an old stage-driver is about
the snugness(70,8)box. When clo(1130,10)whale,(1992,8)very
death-lock(118,8)fight, he handled his unpitying lance coolly and
off-handedly, as a whistling tinker his hammer. He would hum(406,10)old rigadig tunes while flank and flank with(1786,10)exasperated
monster. Long usage had, for this Stubb, converted the jaws of death
into an easy chair. What he thought(45,9) itself, there is no
telling. Whether he ever(62,12)it at all, might be a question;
but, if(59,9)did (2007,8)o cast his mind that way after a
(609,11)(693,9)no doubt, like a good sailor, he took it to be a
sort of call(655,8)watch to tumble aloft, and bestir themselves there,
about something(1911,8)(514,8)find out when he obeyed the order, and
not sooner.

What, perhaps, with other things, made Stubb such(463,8)-going,
unfearing man, so cheerily trudging off(618,10)burden of life in a
world full of grave pedlars, all bowed(2019,8)ground(700,9)ir packs;
what helped to bring(1069,9)at almost impious g(1266,9) of his; that
thing must have been his pipe. For, like his nose, his short, black
little pipe was one(1161,8)regular feature(1127,9)face. You would
almost as soon have expected him to turn ou(1265,9)bunk without his
nose as(20,12) pipe. He kept a whole row of pip(625,8) ready
loaded, stuck in a rack, within easy reach(1399,8)hand; and, whenever
he turned in, he smoked them all out in succession, lighting one from
the(671,8)o the end(1505,8)chapter; then loading them again to be in
readiness anew. For, when Stubb dressed, instead of first putting his
legs into his trowsers, he p(362,11)(35,10)mouth.

I say this continual smok(631,19)one cause, at least, of his
peculiar disposition; for every one knows that this earthly air,
whether ashore or afloat, is terribly infecte(881,10) nameless
miseries(1892,8)numberless mortals who have died exhaling it; and as in
tim(799,9)cholera, some people go about with a camphorated
handkerchief to their mouths; so, likewise, against all mortal
tribulations, Stubb’s tobacco smoke might have operated as a sort of
disinfecting agent.

The third mate was Flask, a native of Tisbury, in Martha’s Vineyard. A
short, stout, ruddy young fellow, very pugnacious concerning whales,
who somehow seem(1358,8)ink(542,8)e great leviathans had personally
and hereditarily affronted him; and therefore it w(293,12) point of
honor with him, to destroy them(1077,9) encountered. So utterly lost
