much it may give it compactness and gloss.

Of late years the Manilla rope h(524,10)American(625,9)almost
entirely superseded hemp as a material for(728,11)s; for, though not
so durable as hemp(1156,8)strong(550,8)far more soft and elastic; and
I will add (since there is an æsthetics(1457,11)ngs), is much more
handsome and becoming(1879,9)oat, than hemp. Hemp is a dusky, dark
fellow, a sort of Indian; but(358,9)is as a golden-haired Circassian
to behold.

T(662,14)is only two-thirds of an inch in thickness. At first
sight, you would not think it so strong as it really is. By experiment
its one and fifty yarns will each suspend a weight of one hundred and
twenty pounds; so that the whole rope will bear a strain nearly equal
to three tons. In length, the(1047,9)perm(980,12)measures
something over two(164,9)fathoms. Towards the stern(1387,9)oat it is
spirally coiled away(1445,8)tub, not like the worm-pipe of a still
though, but so as to form one round, cheese-shaped mass of densely
bedded “sheaves,” or layers of concentric spiralizations, without any
hollow but the “heart,” or minute vertical tube formed at the axis of
the cheese. As the least tangle or kink(1646,9)oiling would, in
running out, infallibly take somebody’s arm, leg, or entire body off,
the utmost precaution is(1863,9)stowing t(1899,8)in its tub. Some
harpooneers will consume almost an(119,8)morning in this business,
