CHAPTER 65. The Whale as a Dish.

That mortal man should feed upon the creature that feeds his lamp, and,
like Stubb,(306,8) by his own light, as you may say; this seems so
outlandish a thing that one must needs go a little into the history and
philosophy of it.

It is upon record, tha(741,8)centuries ago the tongue of the Right
Whale was esteemed a great delicacy in France, and commanded large
prices there. Also, that in Henry VIIIth’s time, a certain cook of the
court obtained a handsome reward for inventing an admirable sauce to be
eaten with barbacued porpoises, which, you remember, are a species of
whale. P(56,10)indeed, are to this day considered fine eating. The
meat is made into balls about the size of billiard balls, and being
well seasoned and spiced might be taken for turt(1047,9)or veal balls.
T(904,8)onks of Dunfermline were very fond of them. They ha(533,9)
(329,8) grant from the crown.

The fact is, that among his hunters at least, the whale would by all
hands be(348,12)a noble dish, were there not so much of him; but
(1990,11)me to sit down(1376,8)a meat-pie nearly one hundred feet
long, it takes(1479,9)r appetite. Only the most unprejudiced of men(1094,13)nowadays partake of cooked whales; but the Esquimaux are
not so fastidious. We all know how they live upon whales, and have rare
old vintages of prime old train oil. Zogranda, on(1072,8)ir most famous
doctors, recommends strips of blubber for infants, as being exceedingly
juicy and nourishing. And this reminds me that(1081,9)Englishmen, who
long ago were accidentally left in Greenland by a whaling vessel—that
these men actually lived for several months on the mouldy scrap(1081,10)s which had been left ashore after trying (1032,8)blubber. Among
the Dutch whalemen these(105,8)are called “fritters”;(1244,8)indeed,
they greatly resemble, being brown and crisp, and smelling something
like old Amsterdam housewives’ dough-nuts or oly-cooks, when fresh.
They have such an eatable look(1718,8)e most self-denying stranger can
hardly keep his hands off.

But what further depreciates(1128,11)as a civilized dish, is his
(664,9) richness. He is the great prize ox(1862,8)sea, too fat to be
delicately good. Look at his hump, which(1268,8)e as(1595,12) as the
buffalo’s (which i(1957,13)rare dish), were it not such a solid
pyramid of fat. B(1655,8)permaceti itself, how bland and creamy that
is; like the transparent, half-jellied, white meat of a cocoanut in the
third month of its growth, yet far too rich to supply a substitute for
butter. Nevertheless, many(813,10)have a method of absorbing it into
some other substance, and then partaking of it. In the long try watches
of the night it is a common thing for(556,8)men to dip their
ship-biscuit into the huge oil-pots and let them fry there awhile. Many
a good supper have I thus made.

In the case of a small Sperm Whale the brains are accounted a fine
dish. The casket(772,9)kull is broken into with an ax(342,10) two
pl(771,8)tish lobe(1561,8)withdrawn (precise(1208,10)ing two large
puddings), they are then mixed with flour, and(1891,8)into a most
delectable mess, in flavor somewhat(123,12)calves’ head(960,8)is
quite a dish among some epicures; and every one knows that some young
bucks among th(62,10), by continually dining upon(146,9)brains, by
and by get to(772,8)littl(473,9)(1997,9)own, so as to be able to
tell a calf’s head from(55,10) heads(1645,16) requires
uncommon discrimination(2006,8)at(1362,8)reason why a young buck with
an intelligent looking(151,13)before him, is somehow one of the
saddest sights you can see. The head looks a sort of reproachfully at
him,(720,9)“Et tu Brute!” expression.

It is not, perhaps, entirely because(1676,11)is so excessively
