CHAPTER 66. The Shark Massacre.

When(849,8)Southern Fishery, a captured Sperm Whale(395,8)long and
weary toil, is brought alongside late at night, i(1903,10)as a general
thing at least, customary to proceed at onc(937,9)business of cutting
him in. F(1098,8)(37,9)is an exceedingly laborious one;(1319,8)very
soon completed; and requires all hands to set about it. Therefore, the
common usage is to take in all sail; lash the helm a’lee; and then send
every one below to his hammock till daylight, with the reservation
that, until that time, anchor-watches shall be kept;(1160,8), two and
two for an hour, each couple, the crew in rotation shall mount the deck
to see that all goes well.

But sometimes, especially upon the Line(1548,8)Pacific, this plan will
not answer at all; because such incalculable hosts of sharks gather
round the moored carcase, that were he left so for six hours, say, on a
stretch, littl(1897,8)han the skeleton would be visible by morning. In
most other part(1388,9)ocean, however, where these fish do not so
largely abound, their wondrous voracity can be at times considerably
diminished, by vigorously stirring them up with sharp whaling-spades, a
procedure notwithstanding, which, in some instances, only seems to
tickle them into still greater activity. But it was not thus in the
present case(829,10)Pequod’s sharks; though, to be sure, any man
unaccustomed to such sights, to have looked over her side th(1309,9)
would have almost thought the whole round sea was one huge cheese, and
those(714,8)the maggots in it.

Nevertheless, upon Stubb setting the(1050,13) after his supper was
conclud(1312,8)when, accordingly, Queequeg and a forecastle seaman came
on deck, no small excitement was created among th(221,8); for
immediately suspend(196,8)cutting stages over the side, and lowering
three lanterns, s(1935,9)ey cast long gleams of light(83,10)turbid
sea, these two mariners, dar(347,8)ir long(785,17)kept up an
incessant murdering(1005,8)sharks,* by strik(433,8)keen steel deep
into their skulls, seemingly their only vital part. But(1368,8)foamy
confusion of their mixed and struggling hosts, the marksmen could not
always hit(68,8)ark(1765,8)is brough(1865,8)new revelation(1254,8)
incredible ferocity(1281,8)foe. They viciously snapped, not only at
each other’s disembowelments, but like flexible bows, bent round, and
b(200,9)own; till those entrails seemed swallow(1014,8)an(9,8)gain
by the same mout(1117,9)oppositely voided by the gaping wound. Nor was
this all. It was unsafe to meddl(1238,11)corpses and g(1782,9)these
creatures. A sort of generic or Pantheistic vitality(233,8)to lurk in
their very joints and bones, after what might be called the individual
life had departed. Killed and hoisted on deck for the sake of his skin,
one(227,9)(2015,8)(1374,8)ook poor(1193,9)’s hand off, when he tried
to shut down the dead lid(111,8)murderous jaw.

*The(1781,14) used for(1177,8)-in is mad(164,8) very best steel;
