CHAPTER 88. Schools and Schoolmasters.

The previous chapter gave account of an imm(958,9) or herd of Sperm
W(1451,8)nd there was also(1706,9)en the probable cause inducing those
vast aggregations.

Now, though such great bodies are at times encountered, yet, as must
have been seen, even(1832,8)present day, small detached bands are
occasionally observed, embracing from twenty to fifty individuals each.
Such(87,10) known as schools. They generally are of two sorts; those
composed almost entirely of fem(400,12)ose mustering none but young
vigorous males, or bulls, as they are familiarly designated.

In cavalier attendance up(1044,8)chool(148,13)you invariably see a
male of full grown magnitude, but not old; who, upon any alarm, evinces
his gallantry by fall(1011,11)rear and covering the(1646,8)of his
ladies. In truth, this gentleman is a luxurious Ottoman, swimming about
over the watery world, surroundingly accompanied by(1128,8) solaces and
endearments of the harem. The contrast between thi(148,9) and his
concubines is striking; because, while he is alway(108,9)largest
leviathanic proportions, the ladies(856,10)(456,9)th, are not more
than one-third(209,8)bulk of an average-sized male. They are
comparatively delicate, indeed; I dare say, not to exceed half a dozen
yards round the waist. Nevertheless, it cannot be denied, that(735,9)
whole(806,10)hereditarily entitled to _en bon point_.

It is very curious to watch this harem and its lord in their indolent
ramblings. Like fashionables,(957,11)or ever(1961,8)move in
leisurely search of variety. You meet them(2019,8)Line in time for the
full flower(672,8)Equatorial feeding season, having just returned,
perhaps, from spend(925,8)summer(1972,8)Northern seas, and so cheating
summer of all unpleasant weariness and warmth. By (1931,8) they have
lounged up and dow(1724,9)menade(231,15) awhile, they start(2022,9)Oriental waters in anticipation(977,8)cool season there(219,8)
evade the other excessive temperatur(145,9)year.

When serenely advancing on on(190,8)se journeys, if any strange
suspicious sights are seen, my lord whale keeps a wary eye on his
interesting family. Should any unwarrantably pert young L(1126,8)
coming that way, presume to draw confidentially close to(227,11)
(1175,8)with what prodigious fury the Bashaw assails him, and chases
him away! High times(1138,8), if unprincipled young rakes like him are
to be permitted to in(477,9)sanctity of domestic bliss; though do
what(179,12)will, he(1193,8)keep the most notorious Lothario out of
his bed; for, alas! all fish bed in common. As ashore(1514,12) often
cause(113,10)terrible duels among their rival admirers; just so with
the whales, who sometimes come to deadly battle, and all for love. They
fence with their long lower jaws,(90,11)locking them together, and
so striving(1253,8) supremacy like elks(667,8)rringly interweave their
antlers. Not a few are captured(1291,8)the deep scar(2019,8)se
encounters,—furrowed heads, broken teeth, scolloped fins; and in some
