CHAPTER 89. Fast-Fish and Loose-Fish.

The allusion(1263,8)waif and waif-poles(1493,8)last chapter but one,
necessitates some account(404,8)laws and regulations(432,8)whale
fishery, of(1910,11)waif may be deemed the grand symbol and badge.

It frequently happens that when several ships are cruising in company,
a whale(122,8)struck by one vessel, then escape, and be finally killed
and captured by another vessel(1859,9)ein are indirectly comprised
many minor contingencies, all partaking of this on(288,8)feature. For
example,—after a weary and perilous chase (181,11) of a whale, the
body may get loose from the ship by reason of a violent storm; and
drifting far away to leeward, be retaken by a second whaler, who, in a
calm, snugly tows it alongside, without risk of life or line. Thus the
most vexatious and(180,9)disputes would often aris(1195,13)
fishermen, were there not some written or unwritten, universal,
undisputed law applicable to all cases.

Perhaps the only formal whaling code authorized by legislative
enactment, was that of Holland. It was decreed by the States-General in
A.D. 1695. But though no other nation has ever had any(264,9)whaling
law, yet the American (333,9) have been their own(207,9)ors and
lawyers in this matter. They have provided a system which for terse
comprehensiveness surpasses Justinian’s Pandects and the By-law(1222,8)
Chinese Society for the Suppression of Meddling with other People’s
Business. Yes; these laws might be engraven on a Queen Anne’s farthing,
or the barb of a harpoon, and worn round the neck, so small are they.

I. A(1595,11)belongs(1573,8)party fast to it.

II. A(1631,11) is fair game for anybody who can soonest catch it.

But what plays the mischief with(491,8)sterly code is the admirable
brevity of it, which (1702,13)a vast volume of commentaries to
expound it.

First: What is a(1874,10)? Alive or dead a fish is technically fast,
when it is connected with an occupied ship or boat, by any medium at
all controllable(938,8)occupant or(12,9)s,—a mast, an oar, a
nine-inch cable, a telegraph wire, or a strand of cobweb, it is all the
same. Likewise(249,27) (248,8)bears a waif, or any
other recognise(2007,9)of possession; so long as(638,11)waifing it
plainly evince their ability at any time to take(1583,15)as well
as their intention so to do.

These are scientific(569,13); but the(591,14)of the whalemen
themselves sometimes consist in hard words and harder knocks—the
Coke-upon-Littleton(101,8)fist. True, among the more upright and
honorabl(150,10) allowances are always made for peculiar cases, where
it would be an outrageous moral injustice for on(1081,8)to claim
(485,10) of a whale previously chased or killed by another party. But
others are by no means so scrupulous.

Some fifty years ago there was a curious case of whale-trover litigated
in England, wherein the plaintiffs set forth that after a hard chase of
(241,8)in the Northern seas; and when indeed they ((104,14)) had
succeeded in(1520,8)ing(531,8)h; they were at last, through peril of
their lives, obliged to forsake not only (41,8)nes,(756,8)ir boat
itself. Ultimately the defendants (the crew of(460,9)ship) came up
with(821,10), struck, killed, seized, and finally appropriated it
before the very ey(908,10)(424,10). A(358,8)thos(169,13)were
remonstra(1455,8), their captain snapped his fingers(464,8)(527,10)’
teeth, and assured them that by way of doxology(1897,8)deed he had
