CHAPTER 104. The Fossil Whale.

From his mighty bulk the whale affords a most congenial theme whereon
to enlarge, amplify, and generally expatiate. Would you, you could not
compress him. By good rights he should only be treated of in imperial
folio. Not to tell over again his furlongs from spiracle to tail, and
the yards he measures about the waist; only think(2015,8)gigantic
involution(1407,8) intestines(812,11)y lie in him lik(1033,8)cables
and hawsers coiled(848,8) the subterranean orlop-deck of a
line-of-battle-ship.

Since I have undertaken to manhandle this Leviathan, it behooves me to
approve myself omnisciently exhaustive(1304,8)(1426,10); not
overlooking the minutest seminal germ(313,9)blood, and spinning him
out to the uttermost coil(57,9)owels. Having already described him
in most(422,8)present habitatory and anatomical peculiarities, it now
remains to magnify him in an archæological, fossiliferous, and
antediluvian point of view. Applied to any other creatu(1424,8)the
(432,9)—to an ant or a flea—such portly terms might justly be deemed
unwarrantably grandiloquent. But when(541,10) is the text, the case
is altered. Fain am I to stagger to this emprise under the weightiest
words(860,8)dictionary. And here be it said, that whenever it has been
convenient to consult on(673,9)course of these dissertations, I have
invariably used a huge quarto edition of Johnson, expressly purchased
for that purpose; because that famous lexicographer’s uncommon personal
bulk more fitted him to compile a lexicon to be used by a(1503,8)uthor
like me.

One often hears of writers that rise and swell with their subject,
though it may seem but an ordinary one. How, then, with me, writing of
