CHAPTER 134. The Chase—Second Day.

At day-break, the three mast-heads were punctually(685,8)afresh.

“(1379,13)” cried Ahab after allowing a little space for the light
to spread.

“See nothing, sir.”

“Turn up all hands and make sail! he travels faster than I thought
for;—the (1137,13)ails!—aye, they should have been kept on her all
night. But no matter—’tis but resting(223,9)rush.”

Here be it said, that this pertinacious pursuit of one particular
whale, continued through day into night, an(28,10)night into day, is
a thing by no means unprecedented(1111,8)South sea fishery. For such is
the wonderful skill, prescience of experience, and invincible
confidence acquired by some great natural geniuses among the Nantucket
commanders; that(1760,10)simple observation of a whale(1771,10)
descried, they will, under certain given circumstances, pretty
accurately foretell both the direction in which(1827,9)(455,8) to
swim for a time, while out of sight, as well as his probable rate of
progression during that period. And, in these cases, somewhat as a
pilot, when about losing sight of a coast, whose general trending he
well knows, and(247,10)desires shortly to return to again, but at
some further point; like as this pilot stands by his compass, and takes
the precise bearing of the cape at present visible, in order the more
certainly to hit aright the remote, unseen headland, eventually to be
visited: so does the fisherman, at(198,14)with the whale; for
after being chased, and diligently marked,(1053,9)several hours of
daylight(1845,8)when night obscur(155,11), the creature’s future
wake(1151,9)the darkness is almost as established to the sagacious
mind(397,8)hunter, as the pilot’s coast is to him. So that to this
hunter’s wondrous(1159,8)the proverbial evanesc(1175,8)(1282,8)writ in
water, a wake, is to all desired purposes well nigh as reliable as the
steadfast land. And(210,8)mighty iron Leviathan(651,8)modern railway
is so familiarly known in its every pace, that, with watches in their
hands, men time his rate as doctors that of a baby’s pulse; and lightly
say of it, the up train or the down train will reach such (1579,8)a
spot, at(24,15)n hour; even so, almost, there are occasions
whe(1212,8)(1534,9)ers time that other(350,18)deep,
according(649,8)observed humor of his speed; and say to themselves, so
many hours hence this(1620,8)ill have gone two hundred miles,(34,10)
about reached this or that degree of latitude or longitude. But to
render this acuteness at all successful(1998,8)end, the wind and the
sea must be(1133,10)man’s allies; for of wh(1326,11)avail to the
becalmed or windbound mariner is the skill that assures him he is
exactly ninety-three leagues and a quarter from his port? Inferable
(2041,8)se statements, are many collateral subtile matters touching the
chase of whales.

The ship tore on; leaving such a furrow(361,8)sea as when a
cannon-ball, missent, becomes a plough-share and turns up the level
field.

“By salt and hemp!” cried Stubb, “but this swift motio(778,11)ck
creeps up one’s legs and tingles at the heart. This ship and I are two
brave fellows!—Ha, ha! Some one take me up, and launch me, spine-wise,
o(307,9),—for by live-oaks! my spine’s a keel. (105,8)we go the gait
that leaves no dust behind!”

“There she blows—(10,9)!(11,11)—right ahead!” was now the
mast-head cry.

“Aye, aye(385,17)I knew it—ye can’t escape—blow on and split
your spout, O whale! the mad fiend himself is after ye! blow your
trump—blister your lungs!—Ahab will dam off your blood, as a miller
shuts his watergate up(409,8)tream!”

And Stubb did but speak out for(1818,12)(1000,8)crew. The frenzies
of the chase had by this time worked them bubblingly up, like old wine
worked anew. Whatever pale fears and forebodings some of them might
have felt before; these were not only now kept out of sight through the
growing awe of Ahab, but they were broken(780,9)on all sides routed,
as timid prairie hares that scatter before the bounding bison. The hand
of Fate had snatched all their souls; and by the stirring perils of the
previous day; the rack(1877,8)past night’s suspense; the fixed,
unfearing, blind, reckless way in which their wild craft went plunging
towards its flying mark; by(214,8)se things, their hearts were bowled
along. T(1791,8)that made great bellie(253,8)ir sails, and rushed the
